1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,679
A good AI answer can still arrive too early.

2
00:00:03,679 --> 00:00:05,642
You ask a question.

3
00:00:05,642 --> 00:00:11,166
The model gives you a fluent paragraph, a clean plan, maybe even a reasonable

4
00:00:11,166 --> 00:00:13,129
recommendation.

5
00:00:13,129 --> 00:00:15,091
It feels like progress.

6
00:00:15,091 --> 00:00:20,616
But sometimes the answer is solving a question you have not actually chosen yet.

7
00:00:20,616 --> 00:00:26,141
By the end of this video, you will have a prompt you can reuse

8
00:00:26,141 --> 00:00:28,343
before any important AI answer.

9
00:00:28,343 --> 00:00:30,546
It checks three things: **Goal.

10
00:00:30,546 --> 00:00:32,508
Grounding.

11
00:00:32,508 --> 00:00:35,449
Ownership.** What are we trying to do?

12
00:00:35,449 --> 00:00:38,021
What facts would change the answer?

13
00:00:38,021 --> 00:00:41,330
And what parts are still mine to choose?

14
00:00:41,330 --> 00:00:44,640
Think of the model as a bright worktable.

15
00:00:44,640 --> 00:00:48,319
It can lay out options, tradeoffs, and missing questions.

16
00:00:48,319 --> 00:00:52,737
But the worktable should not decide what the work is for.

17
00:00:52,737 --> 00:00:55,308
Here is a simple fictional example.

18
00:00:55,308 --> 00:00:58,618
You ask: Should I redesign my onboarding page?

19
00:00:58,618 --> 00:01:04,143
The model might answer instantly: simplify the page, reduce friction, emphasize the main benefit,

20
00:01:04,143 --> 00:01:07,084
add social proof, test a clearer button.

21
00:01:07,084 --> 00:01:09,286
That advice might be useful.

22
00:01:09,286 --> 00:01:12,227
It is also answering a half-built question.

23
00:01:12,227 --> 00:01:14,429
Does “better” mean more signups?

24
00:01:14,429 --> 00:01:16,392
Fewer confused users?

25
00:01:16,392 --> 00:01:18,354
Fewer support tickets?

26
00:01:18,354 --> 00:01:20,557
A more honest first impression?

27
00:01:20,557 --> 00:01:24,605
A clearer explanation of who the product is not for?

28
00:01:24,605 --> 00:01:26,568
Those are different goals.

29
00:01:26,568 --> 00:01:32,092
If you do not name the goal, the model may quietly name it for

30
00:01:32,092 --> 00:01:34,055
you.

31
00:01:34,055 --> 00:01:36,257
The first checkpoint is **Goal**.

32
00:01:36,257 --> 00:01:41,782
Before asking for advice, ask: what am I actually trying to decide or create?

33
00:01:41,782 --> 00:01:45,092
Not just “make this better.” Better for whom?

34
00:01:45,092 --> 00:01:47,054
Better by what measure?

35
00:01:47,054 --> 00:01:49,017
Better at what cost?

36
00:01:49,017 --> 00:01:54,542
A stronger version of the prompt might be: I am deciding whether to redesign

37
00:01:54,542 --> 00:01:56,504
an onboarding page.

38
00:01:56,504 --> 00:01:59,445
The goal is not just more signups.

39
00:01:59,445 --> 00:02:04,970
It is more new users who understand the product and are less likely to

40
00:02:04,970 --> 00:02:07,541
need support in the first week.

41
00:02:07,541 --> 00:02:10,113
Now the model has a scoreboard.

42
00:02:10,113 --> 00:02:14,530
It can still help, but it is not inventing the game.

43
00:02:14,530 --> 00:02:16,733
The second checkpoint is **Grounding**.

44
00:02:16,733 --> 00:02:20,042
Ask: what real-world facts would change the answer?

45
00:02:20,042 --> 00:02:25,567
If the model recommends a redesign, what would make that recommendation stronger or weaker?

46
00:02:25,567 --> 00:02:28,877
Maybe users drop off at the second step.

47
00:02:28,877 --> 00:02:32,556
Maybe support tickets keep mentioning the same confusing sentence.

48
00:02:32,556 --> 00:02:36,235
Maybe recordings show people hesitating over a price detail.

49
00:02:36,235 --> 00:02:40,652
Or maybe the page is not the real problem at all.

50
00:02:40,652 --> 00:02:46,177
So instead of only asking, “explain your reasoning,” try asking: What evidence would change

51
00:02:46,177 --> 00:02:48,140
your recommendation?

52
00:02:48,140 --> 00:02:51,819
Separate what you know from what you are assuming.

53
00:02:51,819 --> 00:02:55,498
That turns the answer into a checklist for reality.

54
00:02:55,498 --> 00:02:59,915
This matters because the goal is not to avoid AI help.

55
00:02:59,915 --> 00:03:04,332
The goal is to rely on it in the right place.

56
00:03:04,332 --> 00:03:09,857
Researchers studying decision support often use terms like automation bias or over-reliance for cases

57
00:03:09,857 --> 00:03:13,167
where people lean too hard on automated recommendations.

58
00:03:13,167 --> 00:03:18,691
And in human-AI decision studies, even explanations can change how people rely on a

59
00:03:18,691 --> 00:03:23,478
system without reliably making them better at telling which recommendations are correct.

60
00:03:23,478 --> 00:03:26,788
So this prompt is not a magic fix.

61
00:03:26,788 --> 00:03:30,097
It does not prove the answer is right.

62
00:03:30,097 --> 00:03:35,622
It does something smaller: it keeps the goal, the evidence, and the human tradeoffs

63
00:03:35,622 --> 00:03:39,301
visible before the advice becomes too easy to accept.

64
00:03:39,301 --> 00:03:41,504
The third checkpoint is **Ownership**.

65
00:03:41,504 --> 00:03:46,290
Some parts of a decision are not facts the model can discover.

66
00:03:46,290 --> 00:03:49,600
They depend on values, context, responsibility, and risk.

67
00:03:49,600 --> 00:03:55,125
For the onboarding page, maybe a shorter version increases signups but gives people a

68
00:03:55,125 --> 00:03:57,087
less accurate expectation.

69
00:03:57,087 --> 00:04:01,874
Maybe a clearer page filters out some users but creates more trust.

70
00:04:01,874 --> 00:04:04,445
A model can describe that tradeoff.

71
00:04:04,445 --> 00:04:08,862
It cannot decide what kind of relationship you want with users.

72
00:04:08,862 --> 00:04:12,911
The same idea shows up in a more everyday example.

73
00:04:12,911 --> 00:04:18,435
Suppose you write: Draft an email telling a collaborator I am unhappy that the

74
00:04:18,435 --> 00:04:20,398
timeline is slipping.

75
00:04:20,398 --> 00:04:23,339
The model can produce a polished email.

76
00:04:23,339 --> 00:04:27,387
But it does not know what you want to protect.

77
00:04:27,387 --> 00:04:29,958
Do you want to repair trust?

78
00:04:29,958 --> 00:04:31,921
Set a boundary?

79
00:04:31,921 --> 00:04:33,883
Get a new date?

80
00:04:33,883 --> 00:04:35,846
Document accountability?

81
00:04:35,846 --> 00:04:37,809
Lower the temperature?

82
00:04:37,809 --> 00:04:40,380
Make the seriousness impossible to miss?

83
00:04:40,380 --> 00:04:42,343
Those are different choices.

84
00:04:42,343 --> 00:04:44,545
The model can show versions.

85
00:04:44,545 --> 00:04:48,224
You choose what you are willing to stand behind.

86
00:04:48,224 --> 00:04:53,749
A better request is: Before drafting, list the possible goals of this message and

87
00:04:53,749 --> 00:04:55,951
the relationship risks of each.

88
00:04:55,951 --> 00:04:59,261
Then give three versions: gentle, direct, and firm.

89
00:04:59,261 --> 00:05:01,833
Separate tone choices from factual claims.

90
00:05:01,833 --> 00:05:05,512
Now the model is doing work on the table.

91
00:05:05,512 --> 00:05:08,453
You are still responsible for the decision.

92
00:05:08,453 --> 00:05:13,977
Here is the whole habit as one prompt: Before answering, help me keep ownership

93
00:05:13,977 --> 00:05:15,940
of this decision.

94
00:05:15,940 --> 00:05:17,902
1.

95
00:05:17,902 --> 00:05:21,212
Restate the goal you think I am pursuing.

96
00:05:21,212 --> 00:05:23,175
2.

97
00:05:23,175 --> 00:05:27,223
List the facts or evidence that would change your answer.

98
00:05:27,223 --> 00:05:29,186
3.

99
00:05:29,186 --> 00:05:33,603
Identify which parts depend on my values, context, or risk tolerance.

100
00:05:33,603 --> 00:05:36,544
Then give advice, separating assumptions from recommendations.

101
00:05:36,544 --> 00:05:39,484
That does not make the model correct.

102
00:05:39,484 --> 00:05:42,794
But it gives you three places to intervene.

103
00:05:42,794 --> 00:05:45,735
If the goal is wrong, correct it.

104
00:05:45,735 --> 00:05:49,414
If the evidence is missing, go look for it.

105
00:05:49,414 --> 00:05:54,939
If the answer depends on values, stop pretending it is only a technical question.

106
00:05:54,939 --> 00:05:57,879
The point is not to think alone.

107
00:05:57,879 --> 00:06:03,404
A good model can widen the room: more options, clearer tradeoffs, sharper questions, and

108
00:06:03,404 --> 00:06:05,976
a second pass on your reasoning.

109
00:06:05,976 --> 00:06:07,938
Use it for that.

110
00:06:07,938 --> 00:06:10,879
Use the model for options and tradeoffs.

111
00:06:10,879 --> 00:06:14,189
Keep the goal, evidence, and final judgment visible.

112
00:06:14,189 --> 00:06:18,237
Before you accept the answer, ask: What is the goal?

113
00:06:18,237 --> 00:06:20,809
What would ground this in reality?

114
00:06:20,809 --> 00:06:23,380
What belongs to me to choose?

115
00:06:23,380 --> 00:06:26,321
Let the AI help you see more.

116
00:06:26,321 --> 00:06:30,000
Do not let it decide what seeing is for.
